content:
OAuth refresh token rotation now works as expected for all instances on Salesforce's first-party infrastructure. Previously, it didn't work for some instances on our first-party infrastructure.

This change applies to Lightning Experience and Salesforce Classic in all editions, but only to instances hosted on Salesforce’s first-party infrastructure. It doesn’t apply to Hyperforce instances.

The date when this change is available depends on your region. For sandboxes, this change is available on August 6, 2024 or August 7, 2024. For production orgs, this change is available on August 7, 2024 or August 8, 2024.

To prepare for this change, confirm whether your instance is located on Salesforce’s first-party infrastructure and check if you have connected apps or external client apps with the OAuth setting Enable Refresh Token Rotation enabled. Test integrations by invoking the OAuth 2.0 refresh token flow at least twice.

If Salesforce doesn't issue a new refresh token with each token request, disable refresh token rotation for apps in production instances. After this change becomes available, enable refresh token rotation for your apps in a sandbox and test that it works as expected before re-enabling it in production.

If you don’t update impacted integrations before this change becomes available, users can get logged out earlier than expected.
title: Update on Refresh Token Rotation in Salesforce
